

Java Modifiers with Banking Real-Time Examples
1. public

A public member can be accessed from anywhere.

Banking Example
class BankService {

    public void checkBalance() {
        System.out.println("Balance: ₹50,000");
    }
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        BankService service = new BankService();
        service.checkBalance();
    }
}

Use Case: Public banking services like Check Balance, Deposit, and Transfer Money.

2. private

A private member can only be accessed inside the same class.

Banking Example
class BankAccount {

    private double balance = 50000;

    public double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        BankAccount account = new BankAccount();

        // account.balance = 100000; // ❌ Compilation Error

        System.out.println(account.getBalance());
    }
}

Output

50000.0

Use Case: Protect balance, PIN, and password from direct access.

3. protected

Accessible in subclasses.

Banking Example
class Account {

    protected void calculateInterest() {
        System.out.println("Calculating Interest");
    }
}

class SavingsAccount extends Account {

    public void display() {
        calculateInterest();
    }
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        SavingsAccount account = new SavingsAccount();
        account.display();
    }
}

Output

Calculating Interest

Use Case: SavingsAccount and CurrentAccount inherit common account functionality.

4. static

Belongs to the class rather than individual objects.

Banking Example
class Bank {

    static String bankName = "State Bank of India";
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        System.out.println(Bank.bankName);
    }
}

Output

State Bank of India

Use Case: Bank name, IFSC code, bank interest policy shared by all accounts.

5. final

Cannot be modified.

Banking Example
class RBI {

    final double MIN_BALANCE = 1000;

    void show() {
        System.out.println(MIN_BALANCE);
    }
}

Trying to modify:

MIN_BALANCE = 2000; // ❌ Error

Use Case: RBI minimum balance, GST percentage, account rules.

6. abstract

Defines common behavior but leaves implementation to subclasses.

Banking Example
abstract class Payment {

    abstract void pay(double amount);
}

class UpiPayment extends Payment {

    @Override
    void pay(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Paid ₹" + amount + " using UPI");
    }
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Payment payment = new UpiPayment();
        payment.pay(5000);
    }
}

Output

Paid ₹5000.0 using UPI

Use Case: UPI, Credit Card, Debit Card, Net Banking all implement payment differently.

7. synchronized

Allows only one thread at a time.

Banking Example
class BankAccount {

    private int balance = 10000;

    public synchronized void withdraw(int amount) {

        balance -= amount;

        System.out.println("Balance: " + balance);
    }
}

If two users withdraw simultaneously, synchronized prevents inconsistent balances.

Use Case: ATM withdrawals, online fund transfers.

8. native

Implemented in C/C++ using JNI.

Banking Example
class FingerPrintScanner {

    native void verifyFinger();
}

Use Case

ATM fingerprint authentication
Biometric login
Smart card reader
9. strictfp

Ensures floating-point calculations are consistent across platforms.

Banking Example
public strictfp class InterestCalculator {

    double calculateInterest() {
        return 50000 * 0.0725;
    }
}

Use Case

Interest calculations should produce the same result on Windows, Linux, and macOS.

Note: Since Java 17, strictfp is rarely needed because floating-point behavior is standardized.

10. transient

Excludes sensitive fields during serialization.

Banking Example
import java.io.Serializable;

class Customer implements Serializable {

    String name = "Sunil";

    transient String atmPin = "1234";
}

After deserialization:

name = Sunil
atmPin = null

Use Case

ATM PIN
OTP
CVV
Session token
11. volatile

Ensures updates made by one thread are immediately visible to other threads.

Banking Example
class ATMServer {

    volatile boolean serverRunning = true;

    public void stopServer() {
        serverRunning = false;
    }
}

When one administrator stops the server, all threads immediately see the updated status.

Use Case

ATM        server status
Payment    gateway availability
Banking          application maintenance mode
